                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d473">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">123 Emmerson, John K.: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-10-25T16:00:00-04:00"
                            >October 25, 1944—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1378. Department has been informed by War Department that Emmerson and Davies are
                    proceeding to Yenan. With their arrival, there will be in the area four officers
                    who, although on detail to Stilwell’s headquarters, are nevertheless secretaries
                    of the Embassy. It is not clear to the Department whether their duties are to be
                    connected primarily with matters of a military character or are to be primarily
                    political and in the field of reporting as seems to be the case with Service. In
                    the latter event the Department is inclined to question either the need or
                    advisability of having four officers in that area and would appreciate receiving
                    your comment on the matter.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stettinius</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
